{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 11:17:49.785544", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Detected anomaly: End-to-end host connectivity is broken, specifically for the 10.0.1.0/24 leaf/host. The issue is localized to leaf_router_0_1’s forwarding plane due to an erroneous blackhole route for its directly-connected host subnet.\\n- Primary faulty device: leaf_router_0_1.\\n- Root cause: A kernel FIB blackhole route for 10.0.1.0/24 on leaf_router_0_1 that overrides normal connected forwarding, causing all traffic to/from 10.0.1.0/24 to be dropped at the leaf.\\n\\nObserved reachability and host state\\n- Host subnets:\\n  - pc_0_0: 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1\\n  - pc_0_1: 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1\\n- End-to-end pings:\\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: timeout\\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: timeout\\n- Local gateway tests:\\n  - pc_0_0 -> 10.0.0.1: OK (0% loss)\\n  - pc_0_1 -> 10.0.1.1: 100% loss\\n  - pc_0_1 -> 172.16.0.7 (leaf_router_0_1): 100% loss\\n  - pc_0_0 -> 172.16.0.5 (leaf_router_0_0): OK\\n- ARP:\\n  - On pc_0_1: 10.0.1.1 MAC present (STALE)\\n  - On leaf_router_0_1: 10.0.1.2 MAC present (STALE)\\n  Interpretation: L2/neigh resolution exists, but L3 replies from the leaf are not returned.\\n\\nControl-plane (BGP) status\\n- All BGP sessions are established across leaves, spines, and super-spine:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) up with both spines; receives/advertises prefixes as expected.\\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201) up with both spines; receives/advertises prefixes as expected.\\n  - spine_router_0_0 (AS 65100) and spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101) see both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 via the appropriate leaves.\\n  - super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000) sees both leaf prefixes via spines.\\n- Conclusion: Control plane is healthy; routes are exchanged as intended.\\n\\nForwarding-plane findings (key evidence)\\n- leaf_router_0_1 (Linux kernel FIB):\\n  - ip route (main table) includes: blackhole 10.0.1.0/24\\n  - FRR RIB reflects this: K * 10.0.1.0/24 [0/0] unreachable (blackhole)\\n  - The expected connected route to 10.0.1.0/24 via eth2 is absent from the main table (though the interface has 10.0.1.1/24 and the local table has the host address).\\n- leaf_router_0_1 interfaces appear up with L2 counters incrementing:\\n  - eth2: 10.0.1.1/24 present; some RX/TX observed.\\n- leaf_router_0_0 has a normal connected route for its host subnet:\\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth2 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.0.1 (no blackhole)\\n- Impact of blackhole on leaf_router_0_1:\\n  - ICMP echo requests from pc_0_1 to 10.0.1.1 will reach the leaf locally (via local table). However, any reply from leaf to 10.0.1.2 is looked up in the main table and matches the blackhole 10.0.1.0/24, so it is dropped. This explains why pc_0_1 cannot ping its own gateway and cannot reach any off-subnet destinations.\\n  - Traffic from elsewhere in the fabric destined to 10.0.1.x will also be dropped at the leaf due to the blackhole.\\n  - pc_0_0 and its leaf function normally.\\n\\nLocalization and root cause\\n- Fault localized to leaf_router_0_1’s data plane.\\n- Root cause: Erroneous kernel blackhole route for 10.0.1.0/24 on leaf_router_0_1. This overrides normal connected forwarding for the local host subnet and drops all traffic to/from 10.0.1.0/24.\\n- Not a BGP/control-plane problem; all sessions and prefix propagation are healthy.\\n\\nScope and impact\\n- All traffic to/from 10.0.1.0/24 is effectively isolated at leaf_router_0_1.\\n- pc_0_1 is unreachable from the rest of the fabric and cannot even exchange IP traffic with its default gateway due to the blackhole.\\n\\nSupporting evidence (verbatim excerpts)\\n- leaf_router_0_1 ip route (main):\\n  - blackhole 10.0.1.0/24\\n- leaf_router_0_1 FRR RIB:\\n  - K * 10.0.1.0/24 [0/0] unreachable (blackhole)\\n- pc_0_1 pings:\\n  - to 10.0.1.1: 100% packet loss\\n  - to 172.16.0.7: 100% packet loss\\n- ARP:\\n  - pc_0_1: 10.0.1.1 lladdr 3a:7e:9f:b1:58:4c STALE\\n  - leaf_router_0_1: 10.0.1.2 lladdr fe:84:57:f4:e3:71 STALE\\n- Healthy side (for contrast):\\n  - pc_0_0 -> 10.0.0.1: 0% loss\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 main table contains normal connected route for 10.0.0.0/24.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network’s control plane is healthy, but the data plane is degraded for the 10.0.1.0/24 leaf/host due to a misinstalled blackhole route on leaf_router_0_1. This is the singular abnormality found and explains all observed connectivity failures involving pc_0_1., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='0f2337fe-acba-4906-bb0b-0f7d209b55c0'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
